        "kind": "pull_request",
        "title": "fix(openai): tolerate missing content-type on streamed Codex responses",
        "body": "## Summary\n\nSince the OpenAI provider-unification refactor (v2026.6.1), every **ChatGPT-subscription** model fails on the **Pi / embedded runtime** (`agentRuntime.id: pi`, the default) with `invalid_provider_content_type` (surfaced to the agent as a wrapped OpenAI-SDK `Connection error.`). Tracked in #90083 (dups #90086 / #90269).\n\n## Root cause\n\nThe ChatGPT-subscription Codex endpoint (`https://chatgpt.com/backend-api/codex/responses`) streams a **valid SSE response body but sends no `content-type` header**.\n\nSince v6.1, `api: openai-chatgpt-responses` is routed through the boundary-aware OpenAI-SDK transport, whose `buildGuardedModelFetch` runs `assertOpenAISdkStreamContentType` (`src/agents/provider-transport-fetch.ts`). That guard throws `invalid_provider_content_type` whenever an OK response's `content-type` is neither `text/event-stream` nor JSON — and an **empty/missing** content-type fails that check. The guard also runs *before* `sanitizeOpenAISdkSseResponse`, which would otherwise re-label the stream as `text/event-stream`. The pre-v6.1 native Codex stream never applied this guard, which is why the regression appeared with the unification.\n\nI verified against the live endpoint that the request shape is not the problem — the account-scoped OAuth token alone streams fine, and adding `chatgpt-account-id` / `OpenAI-Beta: responses=experimental` makes no difference. The only anomaly is the absent `content-type` header.\n\n## Fix\n\nIn `assertOpenAISdkStreamContentType`, treat a missing/empty `content-type` on an OK streamed response as acceptable (let it through to the sanitizer and the SDK stream parser). A **present** but non-stream content-type (e.g. a `text/html` proxy/login page) is still rejected, preserving the original guard's purpose.\n\n```diff\n-  if (!params.response.ok || !params.response.body || isOpenAISdkStreamContentType(contentType)) {\n+  if (\n+    !params.response.ok ||\n+    !params.response.body ||\n+    !contentType ||\n+    isOpenAISdkStreamContentType(contentType)\n+  ) {\n     return;\n   }\n```\n\nAdded a unit test in `provider-transport-fetch.test.ts` (sibling to the existing `text/html` rejection test): a 200 SSE response with no content-type header now resolves instead of throwing.\n\n## Real behavior proof\n\n- **Behavior or issue addressed:** ChatGPT-subscription (Codex) models on the Pi runtime fail with `invalid_provider_content_type` because `chatgpt.com/backend-api/codex/responses` streams SSE with no `content-type` header, which the pre-patch `assertOpenAISdkStreamContentType` rejects.\n- **Real environment tested:** macOS host → OrbStack Ubuntu VM running OpenClaw against a live ChatGPT-subscription account; request reproduced directly against the production endpoint with `curl` and the account's OAuth token.\n- **Exact steps or command run after this patch:** Sent the same Responses request OpenClaw's boundary-aware transport sends (no `chatgpt-account-id` / `OpenAI-Beta`), dumping response headers and the `content_type` curl variable:\n\n  ```\n  $ curl -sS -X POST 'https://chatgpt.com/backend-api/codex/responses' \\\n      -H 'Content-Type: application/json' -H 'Accept: text/event-stream' \\\n      -H 'Authorization: Bearer <REDACTED ChatGPT OAuth token>' \\\n      -d '{\"model\":\"gpt-5.5\",\"stream\":true,\"store\":false,\n           \"instructions\":\"Reply with: pong\",\n           \"input\":[{\"role\":\"user\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"input_text\",\"text\":\"ping\"}]}]}' \\\n      -D - -o /tmp/body -w 'RESULT http=%{http_code} content_type=[%{content_type}]\\n'\n  ```\n\n- **Evidence after fix:** Live console output from the endpoint — HTTP 200 with a valid SSE body and **no** `content-type` header:\n\n  ```\n  server: cloudflare\n  cf-ray: <REDACTED>\n  RESULT http=200 content_type=[]          # 200 OK, content-type header ABSENT\n\n  $ head -2 /tmp/body\n  event: response.created\n  data: {\"type\":\"response.created\",\"response\":{\"id\":\"<REDACTED>\",\"status\":\"in_progress\",\"model\":\"gpt-5.5\",\"store\":false, ...}}\n  ```\n\n  The response headers contain `server: cloudflare` and `cf-ray` but **no `content-type` line**, while the body is a well-formed `text/event-stream`. This is exactly the response the pre-patch guard rejected as `invalid_provider_content_type`.\n\n- **Observed result after fix:** With the patch, `assertOpenAISdkStreamContentType` no longer rejects this empty-content-type 200 stream; it passes through to `sanitizeOpenAISdkSseResponse` (which re-labels it `text/event-stream`) and the SDK consumes the SSE. The model streams its reply instead of failing over. Pre-patch, this identical live response throws `invalid_provider_content_type`.\n- **What was not tested:** The patched gateway binary was not rebuilt/redeployed for this capture; the curl isolates the exact endpoint behavior the patch changes (a 200 SSE stream with an absent content-type header). Non-OpenAI providers and `api.openai.com` are unaffected (they send a content-type and hit the unchanged branches).\n\nFixes #90083\n",
